THE STORY WAS ABOUT A YOUNG CHILD NAMED RAYMOND THAT GREW UP IN A LIBRARY.
HIS FATHER WORKED FOR THE LIBRARY AS A CUSTODIAN AND TOOK A LOT OF PRIDE IN HIS WORK.
WHEN RAYMOND WAS YOUNGER, HE THOUGHT THEY WERE RICH BUT HIS PARENTS ASSURED HIM THAT THEY WEREN'T AND HE GREW UP FEELING DIFFERENT FROM OTHERS.
HE WAS VERY HAPPY LIVING AT THE LIBRARY BECAUSE HE HAD AN ENTIRE WORLD OF BOOKS AT HIS FINGERTIPS WHENEVER HE WANTED.
HE OFTEN WENT TO LOOK THINGS UP EVEN IN THE MIDDLE OF THE NIGHT.
THE LIBRARY IS WHERE HE GAINED HIS THIRST FOR KNOWLEDGE THAN HE CARRIED WITH HIM THROUGHOUT HIS LATER YEARS.
HE BECAME THE FIRST COLLEGE GRADUATE IN HIS FAMILY AND WORKED AS A PROFESSOR AT A COLLEGE.
HIS FATHER WAS VERY PROUD OF HIM.
HE ALSO LOOKS BACK WITH FOND MEMORIES OF HIS CHILDHOOD AND HIS SUCCESSES IN LIFE.
A FUNNY STORY THAT RAYMOND TOLD WAS THAT HE ALWAYS HAD TO BE QUIET DURING THE DAY IN THE LIBRARY, BUT HE COULD RUN AROUND AND BE AS LOUD AS HE WANTED AFTER THE LIBRARY CLOSED FOR THE NIGHT.
THE STORY WAS ABOUT A YOUNG BOY NAMED RAYMOND WHO GREW UP IN A LIBRARY.
HIS FATHER WAS THE CUSTODIAN OF THE LIBRARY AND TOOK A LOT OF PRIDE IN HIS WORK.
HE EVEN WAXED THE TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES.
RAYMOND THOUGHT THEY WERE RICH WHEN HE WAS SMALL BUT HIS PARENTS TOLD HIM THEY WERE POOR AND HE ENDED UP FEELING DIFFERENT AS HE GREW UP.
HE NEVER REALLY BROUGHT ANYONE ELSE HOME AND HE SPENT A LOT OF HIS TIME READING.
HE WOULD LOOK UP ANYTHING HE THOUGHT ABOUT EVEN IF IT WAS 3AM IN THE MORNING.
HIS THIRST FOR KNOWLEDGE CONTINUED INTO HIS ADULT LIFE WHERE HE WENT TO COLLEGE AND BECAME A PROFESSOR.
HIS FATHER WAS QUIET BUT QUITE PROUD OF HIS SON.
RAYMOND WAS THE FIRST PERSON IN HIS FAMILY TO GO TO COLLEGE AND GET A DEGREE.
HE LOOKS BACK AT GROWING UP IN THE LIBRARY WITH FOND MEMORIES AND ATTRIBUTES HIS "THIRST FOR KNOWLEDGE" WITH WHAT HE LEARNED THERE.
RAYMOND ALSO REMEMBERS HAVING TO BE QUIET DURING THE DAYTIME, BUT WAS ABLE TO RUN AROUND AND BE LOUD AFTER THE LIBRARY CLOSED EACH DAY.
THIS WAS A LOT OF FUN FOR HIM AND HE LOOKS BACK AT THESE MEMORIES AND LAUGHS.
